European food inflation has slipped
The acceleration in euro area inflation is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
The euro area's 13 countries saw higher-than-expected price increases in November, with annual inflation of 3.1% recorded after 2.6% in October, the EU's Luxembourg office for statistics reported.
The official forecast was only 3 percent likely, according to Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB) did not cut the key interest rate, unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, saying that a cut would lead to an inflationary spiral, combined with rising commodity prices and easing unemployment.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but close to, 2%.
One analyst believes that the ECB is in the trap of the Twenty-second Rule: it must "talk" about inflation so that it does not have to act on it later.
In Germany, November inflation of 3.3 percent is a 12-year high; in Spain, it rose to 4.1 percent from 3.6.
Eurozone inflation has been fuelled by soaring food and energy prices.
Wheat futures rose 88 percent, and the price of soybeans reached its highest since 1973.
The price of cooking oil and milk products also increased significantly in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil has increased by 52 percent this year, and last month it was nearly $100 a barrel for a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1% to 2.5% this year in 2008 but will fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts expect 12-month inflation to remain around 3% for the next 3-4 months, but the average annual rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to have cut interest rates twice during 2008.
