Many places are sparingly using disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections have been reported in hospitals, mostly due to the misuse of antibiotics.
Hygiene conditions in hospitals, overcrowded beds, and overloaded staff are not conducive to stopping infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
They're also sparing on disinfectants in many places.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John's Hospital.
A man recovering from a serious accident has been found to have antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
The patient has been isolated.
There was a similar infection earlier this year.
A victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but soon returned with an MRSA infection and a major operation that had been delayed because of the bacteria in his system.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-drug-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Dr. Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens must have been registered in hospitals, the rest unknown.
About two thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium is carried in the nose of one third of the population without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e. g. laryngitis, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) are well-receptive to antibiotics and are well-treatable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or improperly, bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and spread rapidly in the wrong hospital environment.
Primarily, it can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or sepsis, in elderly or low-weight patients with transient or persistent immune system dysfunction.
According to the medical director of the John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, such infections are part of the daily routine of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA just isn't there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where they don't test for the pathogen.
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the nursing staff see the patient in rubber gloves and masks, and we have the appropriate antibiotics to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients who are admitted to hospital are first screened for MRSA, but this is not always the way to avoid infection.
It's not fashionable to sample
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current domestic hospital conditions and conditions are not conducive to preventing the emergence and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals, nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients entering and should immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these studies also plays a role in this.
Most cases are detected when the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the epidemiology center's chief medical officer.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are national guidelines for treating certain infections and conditions.
The aim should be to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. to carry out microbiological tests to prevent the development of drug resistance, but this is not always adhered to by hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and primary care, said Böröcz Karolina.
They save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from patient to patient by healthcare workers.
So hand washing, gloves, masks are very important, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by contact, drop-in infection, but isolation of an infected patient is not always possible in the hospital environment in the country.
In fact, the wards were often crowded, with beds often very close to each other, whereas epidemiologically, patients should be at least five feet apart.
Unfortunately, noted Karolina Böröcz, hospitals in disadvantaged financial situations are often short on disinfectants, have few nurses, many patients, and thus are more prone to infections.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate precautions are taken, such infections can be detected less often or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treating MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, so they're fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, it has included the prevention and reduction of MRSA in government programmes.
The programme appears to be successful, with the data reported showing a declining trend in MRSA infections in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of hospital-acquired infections caused by these pathogens as a priority.
