Political Capital: the Hungarian Guard has raised the risk of the country
The Hungarian Guard, which was founded in August of this year with the support of the Jobbik Movement for Hungary, has raised the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital.
The company's "risk warning" stated that the greatest political risk in relation to the activities of the Hungarian Guard was that "the ethnic tension that already exists between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary could be exacerbated by violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to provoke such an act, the research institute added.
As they wrote, this all can be traced back to one of the main failures of Hungarian political actors: "the public debate on the Roma issue was left to representatives of radical and extreme political groups, who could build a political strategy against the Gypsy-Hungarian contrast".
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, empowers extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflict, they believe.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, under the influence of large domestic and international media attention, "significantly worsened the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in the country's stability and democratic development".
They remind us that since the autumn of 2006, as part of the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, which has received increasing publicity and momentum, several organizations calling themselves "national self-defense" associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil organizations, while openly proclaiming the readiness of their members - even armed - for defense (disaster protection, homeland defense, law enforcement) tasks, moreover citing the incompetence of the police, the army, that is, the state", they added.
They noted that this is in keeping with the way that, based on the politics and nonpartisanship of society, various political aspirations are put into the civil garment.
The emphasis on civility and the form of association is therefore not merely a means of avoiding the legal pitfalls of judicial registration for these associations, but also a political strategy.
The analysis shows that the activities of the Hungarian Guard are a risk-increasing factor also in terms of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been mentioned as a potential source of danger in several neighboring states, and some ultra-nationalist political actors in neighboring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
All this affects the political stability of the region", it added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in East-Central Europe, thus increasing political risks for the whole region.
As it was written, the Hungarian Guard's operation is similar to the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose creation was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The background to the formation of the Bulgarian Guard was the mass Roma riots that broke out in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took advantage of this to decide to establish the Guard, saying that the purpose of the organization was "national self-defense".
For the past 17 years, they say, there has been "gypsy terror" in Bulgaria, but the state has remained passive and indifferent, recalls Political Capital.
They added that the initiative had sparked a heated debate in the Bulgarian public.
As they wrote, the increased risk of ethnic clashes is indicated by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organizations have announced that they will create their own guards as a form of resistance.
As the Hungarian Guard's operations so far show similarities with the operation of the Bulgarian National Guard, it cannot be ruled out that the Hungarian Roma will also respond to the threat by organizing their own self-defense, according to a risk warning by Political Capital.
Attila Juhász, research director at Political Capital, told the telegraph office that risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
As you said, they publish their risk assessment every year, and if they see something that could affect the risk, they inform the public, like in this case by issuing a risk warning.
