The Troubling Memories
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Bad Arolsen archive has been made public, documenting the fate of 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime.
The 47 million archival documents, which cover 27 kilometers of shelves in Bad Arolsen, in the state of Hessen, have so far been searchable only for "humanitarian" purposes, that is, to provide individual and named insights for past victims or their descendants.
In May 2006, eleven countries - including Germany, France, Israel, and the United States - agreed to open the archive to researchers and historians.
After all states ratified the convention, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the Bad Arolsen archive will allow historians to research "the transfer of prisoners, the health of camp inhabitants and forced laborers", explains Reto Meistern, director of the archive, which is managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, opposed the publication of the documents, since they contain names and thus confidential information.
For example, some of the deported victims may be allegedly homosexual or mentally disabled.
After the war, the collection of concentration camp records and arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo was started for practical reasons, to identify civilians who had been deported or sentenced to forced labor and to provide evidence of their internment, which could be used to obtain compensation.
Bad Arolsen currently has over 300 permanent employees processing tens of thousands of unique requests.
However, some in the scientific community do not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive to be of high importance.
"These documents contain basically nothing new", declared Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the research center on anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
