There have been rumors of a new music festival in Philadelphia being organized by C3 Presents, but now the promoter and organizer of the event has announced that they will be partnering with Melvin Benn's British production company, Festival Republic, to host the Vineland Music Festival in New Jersey.
"We are honored to be working with someone who is the catalyst of the modern American festival movement", Charlie Jones of C3 told Billboard.com.
C3 also hosts the Chicago Lollapalooza Festival and the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
The Vineland Festival in New Jersey is in the summer, so there's plenty of time for camping.
The festival will be held August 8-10, at a 500-acre private estate about 40 minutes from Philadelphia.
The director of Festival Republic, formerly known as Mean Fiddler, Melvin Benn is one of the most respected festival directors in the world.
In 1989 he started organising the British Reading Festival, which attracts around 80,000 visitors each year.
In 1999, Melvin Benn expanded his range of events by organising the Leeds Festival, and in 2006 Festival Republic launched the Latitude Festival in Henham Park, Suffolk.
Since 2002, Melvin Benn has been co-owner and co-producer of the Glastonbury Festival, which now has a capacity of 177,500 people.
C3's Charlie Jones described the Glastonbury Festival as the 'most inspiring event' he has ever attended, and added that his company and Melvin Benn's company were working together to provide the region with a European-style festival.
"The Philadelphia location was chosen early on, and we worked hard with the Fairmount Parks Commission to put this festival in the heart of Philadelphia", said Charlie Jones.
'We have been pursuing a case with the city and the Commission has shown great enthusiasm for our plan.
Unfortunately, the political maneuvering of the city government has led to the failure of the organization", continued Charlie Jones.
"We were fortunate to have had this conversation with Melvin Benn, and we are now preparing to host a huge festival in another unique venue, ultimately serving the interests of the people of Philadelphia".
C3 Presents revived the Lollapalooza festival in Chicago's Grant Park in 2005, after having already proven their exceptional festival management skills with the Austin City Limits music festival in 2002.
The gross revenue for the two events was $9.8 million and $11.3 million in 2007 respectively.
Both festivals were held in urban settings.
"Melvin Benn's European concept is based on a rural festival, whereas our festivals are usually held in urban green spaces", says Charlie Jones.
Our aim is to somehow combine the two models and create both the rural feel of Europe and the urban feel of America".
Vineland is about halfway between Philadelphia and Atlantic City.
"The people of Vineland, and the mayor himself, are enthusiastically supporting the event", says Charlie Jones.
Although he did not give details of the agreement, he did say that "the terms are favorable enough to allow investment in such a large event in a venue that will hopefully be home to the festival for a long time".
According to Charlie Jones, the festival will be "enormous", with a capacity roughly equivalent to the 80,000-seat Bonnaroo Music Festival in Tennessee.
The bands have already received invitations to the event, but at the time of the press conference, nothing is final.
"Vineland is basically a rock festival, but we're planning a variety of music for everyone to enjoy", says Charlie Jones.
Jones and two partners, Charlie Walker and Charles Attal, are the founders of C3, which won the "best independent event organizer" award at the recent Billboard Touring Awards.
