Congress approves the acquisition of MiFID effective November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary process - which ended today with the congressional vote approving the Senate amendments - the government has initiated a social dialogue on the legislation underlying the law, so that both can be implemented before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups unanimously highlighted the efforts of the representatives and senators in negotiations and agreements to establish the most favorable legislation to protect investors and to regulate in detail the activities of companies in order to ensure the efficient functioning of the market.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Law, will allow the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, broadening the supervisory powers of the Spanish National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new Directive allows the provision of financial advisory services to specialist firms, but also to natural or legal persons, and establishes a new type of financial services company (ESIS) alongside securities dealers, securities agencies and portfolio management companies, namely financial advisory companies (AFI).
In addition, the Act increases the number of systems capable of executing transactions involving financial instruments, thus adding to the regulated secondary markets multilateral trading platforms and internalised order fulfilling systems that compete with existing stock exchange players.
Furthermore, the Act requires investment firms to provide market information on the key aspects of their business profile, their risk-taking and risk management methods, and to keep records of all transactions carried out in order to facilitate the control of the CNMV.
The Congressional Committee on Economic Affairs has introduced a number of amendments, most notably to treat securitised debt as a "complex" asset because of the high risk it poses to investors, as was the case with US subprime mortgages.
On the other hand, the transposition of the Directive was also used to legally define the scope of the activities of those with a degree in economics and entrepreneurship, 30 years after the entry into force in 1977 of the Royal Decree laying down the professional functions which could only be performed by economists.
The Senate also proposed the creation of new players in the financial sector, such as a broker-dealer, who works for someone else, does not need the authorisation of the CNMV and can market products or acquire clients for several investment companies at the same time.
