What kind of insurance is good for me?
Motor insurance, which provides protection for the owner of a motor vehicle against various types of damage, involves a considerable expense and depends on a number of factors, such as age, sex, date of licence, marital status, type of motor vehicle to be insured and type of use.
Getting the car is just the first step.
In fact, choosing the right insurance is often more difficult than deciding what kind of car to buy.
First, we need to know what it is.
Motor insurance is an agreement between the insurance company and the insured.
This agreement takes the form of an insurance contract, which states that the insurance company will pay the fixed insurance premium in order to receive compensation in the event of a loss.
The premium is basically the amount paid for insurance, which is determined by taking into account various factors such as age, gender, the date of obtaining a driver's license, marital status, the type of car to be insured, its use, and so on.
Insurance companies set the premium on the basis of statistics, i.e. the higher the premium, the higher the risk of an accident.
That's why people over 25 or women pay less, because statistically they're less likely to be at risk, because they're more careful.
Similarly, studies have led insurance companies to conclude that married people are less likely to cause accidents than are single people.
The frequency of use of the car is the determining factor.
The more frequently used the greater the chance of an accident.
Insurance companies take a number of factors into account when setting the premium.
The owner must therefore do a thorough search to select the most appropriate form of insurance for his profile.
The following are the most important factors in the selection process, so that the insured person's needs can be best met and a reasonable price can be established.
When taking out insurance, those under 25 face a number of disadvantages, such as lack of driving experience and the freshness of their licence.
Although the ideal is to be insured against all dangers, there are also more economical solutions.
The more cautious drivers can take out full insurance with their car, so they're protected from all hazards and the cost is affordable.
In this type of contract, the insured party pays for some of the damage.
'The amount of the premium that the insured person has to pay depends on the premium; the higher the premium, the lower the premium,' says Luis Noguera, head of First Europa, the Spanish online insurance broker.
Another option is extended third party liability insurance, where the customer insures himself against damage caused to others but not to his own car.
In addition, you will be insured against theft, fire, and loss of your car.
That's good advice.
If you are under 25, be careful and avoid accidents as much as possible, as this will affect the bonus and thus reduce the amount you will have to pay in the future.
The benefits granted in relation to the basic rate of the insurance company are called bonuses.
The penalty for the basic rate is called the malus.
'The amount of the bonus and the premium depends on the insurance company and its profits.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to increase the bonus", explains Noguera.
If they are over 25, it is easier for owners to take out adequate insurance, since the risk of accidents is reduced by the experience gained over the years.
At this time, we recommend that you take out full insurance.
"In general, young people are not yet able to apply their experience to a single accident, even when driving", says the Spanish director of a European insurance company, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, when drivers have already overcome the fear of newcomers.
If you are already married but do not have children, it is best to take out a comprehensive insurance policy, provided that your financial situation allows it.
Insurance companies consider married couples with children to be the least risky clients, so the premium is lower for them.
In this case, it is best to have a complete insurance coverage for the parts themselves (up to 300 euros), or if you have a higher premium, you can extend the coverage to cover damage caused to others from the third year of the motor vehicle.
"They drive more calmly, but at the same time they have more customers and can afford to have a higher self-pay", confirms Luis Noguera.
For pensioners, the full insurance is recommended in instalments (around EUR 150), or it can be extended to cover liability insurance if the premium is higher.
Motor vehicle insurance is very important, not only because it provides protection for the owner in the event of an accident, but also because it is a major expense, so it is essential to choose the right form of insurance for you.
