New fears over Russian-Ukrainian gas dispute
A gas dispute has erupted between Ukraine and Russia, which could affect Russian fuel to be shipped to Western Europe.
Much of the Russian gas exported to the European Union (EU) passes through Ukraine, and disputes between the two nations are always the subject of intense attention.
Kiev has stated that if Moscow raises the price of gas paid by Ukrainians, they will also hit Russia with a higher transit cost.
One, the drop in supplies to EU countries, was the result of a previous dispute between the two countries that erupted last year.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow involves the attempted agreement between the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned natural gas monopoly, Gazprom, on the price of gas that Ukraine will pay to Russia in 2008.
Gazprom stated that a 50% price increase over the 2008 price agreement with Ukraine should be implemented for gas produced from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
According to analysts, this could mean a 40% increase in the price of Gazprom's shipment to Ukraine.
'It is important that we make the case during the negotiations as one of the most important transit countries for natural gas,' Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinah told Reuters.
"Changes in gas prices should definitely be linked to the debate on the cost of transit through Ukraine (and to Western Europe)".
As a result of the latest major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom closed the pipeline to Ukraine in January 2006.
This resulted in a domino effect on exports to Western Europe, which also significantly depressed prices.
One quarter of the European Union's gas supply is Russian gas.
Russia has the largest natural gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains unexplored.
As a result, Gazprom supplies its own gas supply to Turkmenistan and other former Soviet states in Central Asia.
The NHS 'must control foreign workers'
NHS boards in Scotland should improve their checks on criminal records of workers coming from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
The proposal was put forward by the Auditor General, Robert Black, after a doctor in Scotland, a foreign national, was linked to the attack at Glasgow Airport in June.
Mr Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland did not have accurate figures on the number of overseas workers.
However, it also identified key controls that were carried out properly in its report, using a sample of five health authorities.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the Auditor-General checked the list of employees recruited from outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi-born doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep crashed into the main terminal of the building.
Abdullah was one of three doctors who were questioned by video link at the Old Bailey on charges of attempted car bombings in the UK in October.
NHS committees must check the qualifications and work experience of their staff from overseas countries and their UK work permits before they begin to work.
Although the Scottish Health Boards use Disclosure Scotland to check criminal records, the agency is not authorised to obtain such information from outside the United Kingdom.
The Auditor General's report suggested, amongst other things, that the committees introduce the Criminal Records Bureau's guide, which facilitates the employer's control processes with various overseas countries.
"While evidence of such checks has been found in personnel records, they are not carried out on a regular basis", states the report.
Black said that while the Scottish NHS had a high level of performance in its pre-employment screening process, he added: 'Our report highlights areas of improvement in the system to ensure we have up-to-date information on the number of overseas staff in the NHS.'
Dr. Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, said it was "highly unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS staff who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
'The report shows that the pre-employment checks currently in place are working well in NHS Scotland and the value of the recommendations is not yet clear,' she added.
The Scottish health authorities estimate that their current overseas staff, consisting mainly of doctors and nurses, is 1,161.
However, the Auditor-General pointed out that the figures are likely to be higher, partly due to the fact that committees have problems identifying staff on indefinite leave.
The investigation also showed that the control procedures implemented in the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, the Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are highly coordinated.
These procedures included the control of passports, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently examining the guidelines and guidance on pre-employment checks for NHS overseas staff.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was delighted to see this task completed after the Glasgow airport attack.
He added that the Scottish Government, in cooperation with the Health Committees, would take into account the recommendations in the report and ensure that the updated guidance on pre-employment checks for all staff, including those from overseas, reflected best practice.
Joy Division is in the movie awards
The biopic of the late lead singer of Joy Division, Ian Curtis, Control, has won five awards at the British Independent Film Awards - including Best Film.
Also awarded were the lead actor, Sam Riley, who worked in a warehouse before Curtis's role, and director Anton Corbijn and supporting actor Toby Kebbell.
The best actress award went to Dame Judi Dench for her performance in the thriller "Details of a Scandal".
And the Variety award for bringing British film into the international spotlight went to Bond actor Daniel Craig.
The awards were presented at a ceremony at the Roundhouse in London.
Control follows Curtis' rise through the ranks of Joy Division to 1980, when he committed suicide at the age of 23.
The black and white film, which also features The Killers, David Bowie and New Order on the soundtrack, cost just £3 million to make.
The Dutch photographer Corbijn - who previously made his name with the cover of U2's "Joshua Tree" - did win two awards; best director and best new director.
Rock music was another highlight of the ceremony; Julien Temple's film about Joe Strummer, the lead singer of the Clash, won the award for best documentary.
The Best Actor award went to Viggo Mortensen for his performance as the driver of the mafia boss in David Cronenberg's London thriller Murdered Promises.
Ray Winstone, known for his tough-guy roles, has been awarded the Richard Harris Award for his outstanding contribution to the British film industry.
The 50-year-old actor, whose credits include "Scum", "Scoop", and "Sexy Dog", is currently filming "Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull".
Winstone is proud to accept the award named after his "Camelot" and "Harry Potter" star, Harris, who passed away in 2002.
"People like Richard Harris and Albert Finney have opened doors for people like me", Winstone added.
"I feel truly fortunate to have met Richard Harris on more than one occasion.
Richard Harris' style is close to me, he was a great actor of his time and I have a great respect for him".
The selection of the independent film awards, known as Bifa, is decided by a panel of filmmakers, actors and festival organizers.
Bifa's supporters and patrons include Mike Figgis, Ken Loach, Ewan McGregor, Samantha Morton, Bill Nighy, Meera Syal and Michael Winterbottom, who are also the founding members of Bifa.
208 people arrested in Saudi Arabia in connection with a terrorist plot
Saudi Arabia announced yesterday that it had arrested 208 militants affiliated with terrorist cells who were planning an imminent attack on an oil refinery and a series of attacks on church personnel and security forces.
State television in the world's largest oil exporter says one of the cells was trying to smuggle missiles.
Al-Qaeda supporters have launched a campaign against the monarchy, which has been an ally of the United States since the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
According to a television report, a cell of eight men led by a resident of foreign nationality planned to launch an attack on an oil facility in the eastern province.
Following an attempted Al-Qaeda attack on the world's largest oil refinery in Abqaiq in 2006, Saudi Arabia began building a 35,000-strong rapid reaction force to protect the facilities.
The report, quoting the interior minister, said that 18 of those arrested belonged to a cell led by a "rocket-firing specialist" who crossed the border illegally.
The report also said that the militants tried to smuggle eight bullets into the kingdom.
Of those arrested, 22 were plotting attacks against church leaders and security forces.
The government has called on church leaders to take a tougher line against the flow of Saudis into Iraq to join Al-Qaeda fighters fighting allied forces and the US-backed Shiite Muslim government, who are considered heretics by Saudi hardline Sunnis.
Al-Qaeda fighters are seen by a significant number of Saudi religious leaders as being drawn into the political circle of the royal family that controls the government.
The group's fighters, spurred by calls by Saudi-born Al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden for the targeting of the pro-Western Saudi government, have targeted foreign settlements, government buildings, and energy facilities.
"The security forces have made a tremendous effort in the last...five months", an Interior Ministry spokesman told state television.
The arrests included a 16-person "media cell" in Medina that was aimed at spreading "takfiri thinking", the ideology of Sunni Muslim radicals that advocates violent action against Muslims who are branded disloyal and apostate.
The arrested also included 32 individuals accused of providing financial support to the militants.
The climate of Venus may provide a glimpse into Earth's future
Scientists yesterday said Venus once had a pleasant environment.
Data from a European spacecraft orbiting the planet suggests that this planet may be considered more of a capricious twin to Earth than we previously thought.
Venus is Earth's nearest planetary neighbor.
The two planets are almost the same size and orbit, although Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Scientists now know that billions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions very similar to Earth's, and even habitable conditions.
But with a dramatically high carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion from solar radiation and a slower rotation rate, Venus has entered a radically different evolutionary path.
Today, the planet's water has evaporated, its surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it's being ravaged by hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, based on a year-long study of the planet, paint a sobering picture of how similar catastrophic climate changes could take place on Earth.
Fred Taylor, professor of physics at Oxford University and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is beginning to be understood why the climate of Venus differs so much from that of Earth, despite the fact that the two planets are very similar in structure.
"Our new data has allowed us to develop a scenario for the formation of Venus billions of years ago, when it might have had Earth-like habitable conditions.
