Mitt Romney says it's not appropriate for a presidential candidate to answer questions from a snowman.
But the Republican presidential candidates did agree to participate in a YouTube-streamed debate, in which ordinary voters recorded their questions on video and passed them on to the candidates.
None of the questions posed on Wednesday night, November 28th, turned out to be as ridiculous as the one posed by the snowman who asked the Democrats about global warming in the other party's YouTube debate.
But the questions and answers this time reflected the state of the Republican Party as we approached next year's elections.
It's not yet known how the CNN executives who co-financed the debate selected the YouTube clips to be distributed to the candidates.
The longest question in the first half-hour debate was on immigration.
This is one of the Republican party's most contentious issues.
CNN asked some voters who were unsure if they were being told something that was troubling them to say, "I've heard a number that the moderator has found to be a strong consensus when the candidates have been tough on the border issue".
The most intense and longest debate was between Rudy Giuliani, who was leading the nation, and Romney, who was leading the polls in Iowa and New Hampshire.
Giuliani is trying to change the perception that he's been too lax on the issue of illegal immigration during his time as mayor of New York.
He accused Romney of hiring illegal immigrants to build his former Massachusetts governor's house.
The debate between the two became particularly heated when the questioner asked about supporting "amnesty" (which would grant permanent status and citizenship to illegal immigrants).
Some of the candidates with fewer votes - such as Representatives Duncan Hunter of California and Tom Tancredo of Colorado - have managed to delve deep into the issue.
And although none of them are considered likely candidates, their continued presence in the race may be explained by the fact that they were the first to raise the immigration bell.
At least on the issue of immigration, there is a broad consensus among the candidates: a common goal of strengthening borders and a strong stance against illegal immigrants.
This issue, along with the fear of Chinese toys and other worries from the outside world, is helping to obliterate or minimize the divide between libertarians and Christian conservatives within the Republican ranks.
When other issues came up, however, the debate turned unpleasantly violent.
Giuliani was faced with the question of why he had supported gun control in the past.
John McCain and Romney argued over whether simulated drowning constitutes torture.
Another questioner wanted to know if the candidates believed every word of the Bible.
Stumbling over this question, Giuliani finally settled on the view that, although he considered the Bible to be his favorite book, he might not take the story of Jonah and the whale literally.
Another question was raised as to whether Jesus would approve of capital punishment.
And so, in the face of expectations, Mike Huckabee, the first-place finisher in the just-concluded Iowa primary, who credits his victory to a strong Christian conservatism, responded by saying that the death penalty is painful, but it's necessary.
When asked if Jesus would have sufficient support, he laughed and said that Jesus was wiser than to run for office.
The competition remains unusually open.
Huckabee's spirited rise in Iowa coincides with libertarian Ron Paul's fund-raising drive and the enthusiastic cheers he received at Wednesday's debate.
The sudden breakthrough of the two candidates can be explained by the fact that the two wings of the party have not yet been able to launch a joint candidate from among aspirants representing more familiar and traditional principles.
In 1980 and in 2000, there was a candidate who united the party, who timely and convincingly proclaimed a victorious message of American greatness, and who found a common voice with both wings of the party.
But now the party is divided, and the consequences are unforeseeable.
Labour Party pain
Another gap before Gordon Brown; the way out remains unchanged
In the face of British political scandals, this one doesn't seem too spicy.
No one has sold their honor, no politician has had his Paris hotel bills exposed, no one has committed an extramarital scandal.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman had secretly contributed over 650,000 pounds ($1.3 million) to the governing British Labour Party for over four years under the names of others, and that the party had not reported this, is one of the things that the circumstantial Gordon Brown would have done well without.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister was voted out of office, and when he made a rash statement that the outcome of the election was not influenced by the polls, he questioned the intelligence of the British people, people still hoped that Brown would provide a strong and effective government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the Liberal Democrat's deputy leader, noted with increasingly witty remarks, the once-feared Brown Stalin has morphed into Mr. Bean.
The failure to rescue the distressed bank Northern Rock exposed regulatory weaknesses and shortcomings in judgment.
The sick proposals to change the tax law encouraged business interests to join forces with the government.
The leak of 25 million people's personal data by the IRS exposed an unimaginable level of administrative incompetence.
In the House of Lords, three Western generals have sparked a riot, protesting against the cuts to the army budget, saying that the position of Minister of Defence is a part-time job.
And now here are the secret donations of David Abrahams, Peter Watt, the general secretary of the Labour Party, who has resigned.
These accidents don't mean that Brown can't turn back on the way to the exit.
At the same time, governments can reach a point beyond which control is impossible.
People don't like politicians and don't trust them, but when a new group comes to power, they usually suspend their disbelief.
But as it becomes clear that the prime minister is unlikely to be able to see things ahead, and may not stay in office for long, the suspension of disbelief ends: the civil service begins to leak, cabinet ministers go into briefings, the press looks for bad news, and the government becomes defensive and unable to focus.
In a sense, Brown is in a particularly difficult position, since unlike other political leaders, he is not considered to be "fresh blood".
As much as he'd like to deny his connection to Tony Blair, he was his right-hand man.
The problems with Northern Rock and the IRS records, for example, are tied to decisions made during Brown's Treasury Department.
And while he was not directly involved in Blair's misdeeds, such as the protracted investigation into the relationship between the "nobility for money" case and political party funding, voters are entitled to assume otherwise.
While Brown's situation is uncomfortable, it's not as embarrassing as it looks.
The shootings are not as frightening as those toros make them out to be.
Just like Mr. Bean, no one died, no one was directly recruited.
