If you think of Sweden and Fallada as being connected, you're thinking of Ike and not Andy Warhol.
Or did you?
At present, Swedish-made wall boxes cast a dark shadow over Warhol's catalog of works.
The 94 'Stockholm type' Brillo Boxes listed here are mostly forged.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen had questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo Box a few months earlier, an internal investigation by the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now come up with a sobering result: A copy of the six "Brillo Boxes" donated to the Moderna Museet by former museum director Pontus Hultén in 1995 - and most likely a hundred more "Stockholm-type" Brillo Boxes in circulation internationally.
The back story is a long and complicated, bewildering chain of artistic and curatorial antics.
Warhol created the first "Brillo Boxait" in New York in 1964 - painted wallpapers based on the red-blue-white pattern of the "Brillo" soapbox.
At a 1968 exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet, with Warhol's consent, hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard were displayed: These were not (for cost-saving reasons) from Warhol, but were shipped directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It wasn't about art, it was about patterns, simple exhibits.
However, Warhol granted permission in 1968 for some Brillo bottles to be made in Sweden, but these were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the era now speak of fifteen boxes that, as authenticated Original-Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Boxes at the time, rightfully entered the history of art and auction under the designation "Stockholm type".
Some of them have sold for over $100,000.
The problem, however, is that Pontus Hultén, the legendary museum director, later falsely claimed that in 1968 a hundred boxes were produced and displayed in Sweden on wheels, which he then left to Warhol.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not made until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, however, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined the six Brillo Boxes owned by the museum, as well as three boxes in Swedish private ownership, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968. The pressed rotating boards were first laid down and polished, then the white oil paint was brushed up.
However, the structure of the copies from 1990 shows that the paint was applied directly to the rotary board by means of a paint roller without a base - and it is not oil paint but acrylic paint.
"These boxes have not been authenticated by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol Brillo Boxes", says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet. "The Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York will not decide otherwise, and the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibiting material".
Of course, the Authentication Board announced back in June that it was investigating soapbox cases for "serious charges".
Since then, however, they have been cloaked in implacable silence.
